            "fact_text": "<ul><li>The oldest rings, found in Sumer (c. 2500 BCE) weren’t for beauty but seals used to sign agreements. Wearing one meant you were a person of authority who could authenticate documents.<br/></li><li>For Egyptians, the ring’s circle symbolised eternity. They believed its open centre was a portal to the unknown and the afterlife.<br/></li><li>In ancient Rome, women received iron rings that symbolised a binding contract, not love. Gold came later but the idea of rings marking commitment started with something as unglamorous as iron.<br/></li><li>In medieval times, bishops wore gemstone rings carved with emblems, using them as wax seals to show power. The deeper the engraving, the higher the authority. <br/></li><li>For most of history, engagement rings had no diamonds. The diamond tradition exploded only after a 1947 campaign coined “A Diamond is Forever.” It rewired global culture and created a new meaning around rings.</li></ul>"
