            "fact_text": "<ul><li>The oldest pendants (c. 40,000 BCE) were made from shells, bones and animal teeth, worn as trophies of survival or strength.<br/></li><li>Across ancient cultures, pendants held spiritual power. Egyptians wore scarabs for rebirth while Mesopotamians wore cylinder seals as charms against evil.<br/></li><li>Pendants were the world’s first “mini art pieces”. Artisans carved intricate figures and patterns into stone and gold, tiny sculptures worn on the body.<br/></li><li>Romans wore bullae - pendants filled with herbs or charms to protect children from evil spirits. Over centuries, these evolved into Renaissance lockets carrying portraits, secrets or love notes.<br/></li><li>Today, solitaires, initials, zodiac symbols and minimal motifs represent self-expression - a continuation of the pendant’s 40,000-year role as a personal emblem.</li></ul>"
