            "fact_text": "<ul><li>The oldest bracelet ever found is 40,000 years old and shockingly advanced. Crafted by the Denisovans in Siberia, its precise drill marks are so fine that even modern jewelers struggle to replicate them.<br/></li><li>Vikings and tribal cultures used metal arm rings that could be broken into pieces and used as currency in trade transforming bracelets into tools of commitment and trust.<br/></li><li>Bracelets moved from practicality to expressive culture: Indus Valley women wore stacked bangles for sound, rhythm, marriage and festivals. Bracelets now expressed prosperity and social meaning.<br/></li><li>With jade bracelets, the category evolved into spiritual protection: A cracked bracelet meant the bracelet had saved someone's life. Bracelets became guardians, not just accessories.<br/></li><li>Charm bracelets revolutionised the category. Each charm symbolised a memory or milestone. Bracelets became wearable biographies, holding love, loss, travel and dreams. For the first time, bracelets captured personal stories rather than cultural ones.</li></ul>"
